@pmwqld 

> We would like to use such a feature to implement an AUTO Dead Letter Queue (DLQ). Any messages that cannot be processed from the main topic can be sent to the AUTO DLQ topic and only become "visible" after a particular time depending on the retry and backoff algorithm.

I think if all messages with the same delay time in the topic, use Dead Letter Queue can match this scene. otherwise the dispatcher logic in broker and limited by the receive queue will affect the delay result.

@nkurihar the issue is that proxies are exposed to the world, so more likely to be compromised. If the proxy is compromised at that point that proxy has full control of the system. With TLS and without proxyRoles, there's no way to block this access without regenerating all certs. With TLS and proxyRoles, you just need to reconfigure proxyRoles to exclude the role of the proxy that was compromised.
(thinking out loud here) But in this case, the proxy would fall back to being a normal role, and since the proxy role needs access to all the resources, it would still have access to the same resources.

Again, other opinions would be very useful here, especially from the people who originally added proxy roles. @merlimat @jai1 @joefk @massakam @sijie

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <openssl/bio.h>
#include <openssl/evp.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    char input[] = "YWJjZGVmZ2hpamtsbW5vcHFyc3R1dnd4eXo=";

    BIO *bio, *b64;
    size_t length = strlen(input);
    char *result = (char *)malloc(length);

    memset(result, '#', length);
    result[length - 1] = '\0';

    bio = BIO_new_mem_buf((void *)input, -1);
    b64 = BIO_new(BIO_f_base64());
    bio = BIO_push(b64, bio);

    BIO_set_flags(bio, BIO_FLAGS_BASE64_NO_NL);
    int x = BIO_read(bio, result, length);
    /* result[x] = '\0'; */
    BIO_free_all(bio);

    printf("%d %s\n", x, result);

    free(result);

    return 0;
}
```

